title: For Sale/Trade:  SIG Sauer SP 2022 in 9mm
postcontent:
I am selling/trading my slightly used SIG Sauer SP 2022 chambered in 9mm.

I originally purchased this handgun for my wife for home defense while I was out on business trips.  Unfortunately, she doesn't particularly care for its DA/SA control/firing method, and would rather have a larger version of her Glock G26.  So, this gun is for sale, or up for trade for a Glock G17/19/22/23 either GEN 3 or 4.  Would also consider a Smith and Wesson M&P in 40 S&W or 9mm (she likes her dad's M&P40c).

I will provide SIG's description of this particular weapon......

The SIG SAUER® SP2022® is the latest version of our popular polymer framed pistol and features a durable, lightweight and wear-resistant polymer frame with the added tactical versatility of an integrated accessory rail. The slide is machined from a solid block of stainless steel and protected by SIG’s black Nitron® finish. Available in 9mm, and .40 S&W. It also features the SIG SAUER four-point safety system. The SIG SAUER polymer framed pistols has earned an enviable reputation and proven track record of reliable performance in the hands of law enforcement professionals. In December of 2004 the U.S. Army Tank-automotive and Armaments Command at the Rock Island Arsenal awarded SIG SAUER a contract for 5,000 SIG SAUER SP2022 pistols chambered in 9mm. 

And these excerpts are from a review on The Truth About Guns blog.......

The SP2022 may look a tad different than the P226 on the outside, but it bears a striking resemblance on the inside. The guns’ functions are identical, both in terms of trigger feel and the single action/double action mechanics. The grip shape is close enough for rock and roll. The SP2022′s slide’s general design and extractor echo classic SIG cues. But there are some distinct differences . . .

The first thing SIG aficianados usually notice: the SP2022′s grip. Unlike Yael Goldman’s cleavage, it’s made of plastic. While the SP2022′s polymer handle may not be as strong as steel who’s gonna break it? You? The SP2022′s significantly lighter than the P226 (a.k.a., ballistic boat anchor); suitable for everyday carry. The younger sib’s improved texture also makes it a lot more grippy.

The SP2022′s “chassis” is made of steel. The actual bits that move along the rails of the slide and keep the gun running are also metal, set into the grip. The SP2022 doesn’t have full-length rails like the P226, but again, do you need that level of build quality for non-special ops? And if you do, pay up. Meanwhile . . .

The SP2022′s slide stop extends past the trigger. That’s because the SP2022 uses a 1911-like system to hold everything together. The same pin that holds the slide stop in place keeps the barrel link and the slide together. The SP2022 also takes down much like a 1911; the slide stop comes out when you match up the right holes.

Another nifty feature: the improved decocker. It’s shorter, quicker, and feels a little better than the old version. SIG’s redesigned the magazine release in a Benelli-style triangle shape instead of ye olde SIG circle.

The DA trigger pull is 10lbs.  The SA trigger pull is 4.4lbs.  It's weight with a magazine is 29.0oz.  It's magazine capacity is 15 rounds of 9mm.  And it comes with 3-dot white-dot contrast sights.

SIG's MSRP for this weapon is $513.00, and you can usually find them for sale NIB for $450-600 depending on the slide, caliber, and sight configuration online or at your local gun store.

This gun has less than 150 rounds in it, and cleaned after each 50.

Also will come with an additional 15 round capacity magazine (it only came with one NIB from SIG when I bought it).

Would prefer to do any deal in Columbia, SC and avoid having to ship via FFL to FFL and all the headache, but will if you are serious.

Message me with any questions you have.

I will say, it is a pleasure to shoot, and has been pretty accurate with even bulk ammo.  Good little pistol, but the wife prefers her Glock.  I have never been a Glock guy, but they are dependable.........and ugly.  Lol.

title: For Sale:  Rare WWII Romanian Contract Beretta M1934 .380 ACP Pistol W/2 WWII Mags
postcontent:
Rare Romanian Contract Beretta M1934 .380acp Pistol W/2 WWII Mags. Here is a Romanian contract Model 1934 Beretta military pistol assembled in 1941, as indicated by the markings on the left side of the slide, and with two original WWII Beretta magazines. The back of the right side of the frame displays Romanian armory mark, "CM". 
NO import markings!
CONDITION: Excellent, with 97-98% of original blue still on the metal. All matching serial numbers (frame, slide, barrel). Fine bore with strong and shiny rifling. Very smooth action. Difficult to find pistol without the import marks! Caliber: 9 mm Short (.380 ACP, marked on barrel). Two WWII Beretta magazines with thin metal floor plates and no other markings, both in like new condition (as is the pistol!).

This Beretta model 1934 pistol offered here was manufactured for the Romanian military in 1941. In August of 1940, the Romanian military placed a contract with Beretta for 61,000 model 1934 pistols. This contract specified that the pistols were to be delivered within seven months. The first of these pistols was not delivered until February of 1941 due to the shortage of steel and Romania's failure to send Beretta the entire fund amount for the pistols. Beginning in February of 1941, Beretta delivered 10,000 pistols with the promise of 5,000 more per month until the total contract was filled. By August of 1941, Beretta had sent a total of 40,000 pistols, but the remaining 21,000 were never delivered. This means that there are less then 40,000 of these pistols in existence today. The first of these Romanian contract pistols can be identified with a 0(zero) at the beginning of the 5 digit serial number. The Romanian contract pistols are identical to the Italian model 1934 versions except that the slide is marked 9 SCURT instead of 9mm Corto as seen in the pictures below. These Romanian model 1934 pistols were normally issued to the Romanian officers 
during WW2.
$1150.00

title: For Sale:  H & R ARMS M1 GARAND SEMI AUTO RIFLE-1954 BRL DATE       W/ NATIONAL MATCH STOCK & OTHER PARTS
postcontent: Very good condition Harrington & Richardson (H & R Arms Co.) mfg. M1 Garand semi auto rifle in .30-06 caliber that is NOT import marked and is mechanically tight and excellent. Barrel is marked HRA and dated 9-54 for September 1954. Trigger group is marked SA for Springfield, bolt is also Springfield. Op rod is Remington National Match mfg, as is the front sight. Stock has glass bedding and a serial number in the right side buttstock, both characteristic of a National Match stock. Metal finish is nice original gray parkerized showing a little normal wear. Bore is very good with strong rifling. Walnut stock has attractive original finish and shows some handling marks. Left side of wrist has a DOD eagle cartouche, underside of wrist has a circle P cartouche. A nice looking H & R Garand that will make a fine addition to your collection and a great shooter.
